Tag-name shell injection exposes release signing secrets
Link: https://chatgpt.com/codex/cloud/security/findings/2f0c990bbe8c8191956fa87f0f34bc8c?sev=critical%2Chigh
Criticality: high (attack path: high)
Status: new

# Metadata
Repo: hatolife/ClipForVRChat
Commit: 0fb2dfe
Author: poppo@hato.life
Created: 2026/6/29 13:19:07
Assignee: Unassigned
Signals: Security, Validated, Patch generated, Attack-path

# Summary
Introduced. The newly added `cp` commands in the secret-bearing Bash signing step use the untrusted GitHub ref name directly in shell source. The ref should be passed through an environment variable and validated/sanitized, or release tags should be strictly validated before use in shell commands.
The commit adds Bash commands that copy signature and public-key artifacts to filenames containing `${{ github.ref_name }}`. Because GitHub Actions expression interpolation happens before the shell runs, a tag name containing shell metacharacters such as a double quote and semicolon can break out of the quoted destination path and execute arbitrary Bash commands. This step has `CI_RELEASE_GPG_PRIVATE_KEY`, `CI_RELEASE_GPG_PASSPHRASE`, and `CI_RELEASE_GPG_FINGERPRINT` in the environment, has already imported the private key into `GNUPGHOME`, and runs before the final zip packaging. An attacker able to trigger this release workflow with a crafted tag name could exfiltrate the release signing key/passphrase or modify and re-sign packaged artifacts.

# Validation
## Rubric
- [x] Confirm the workflow can run from attacker-controlled tag refs matching v* and that the ref value is later used as github.ref_name.
- [x] Confirm the affected step is bash and has release signing secrets in its environment.
- [x] Confirm the commit introduced direct github.ref_name interpolation into shell commands without sanitization or env indirection.
- [x] Confirm a syntactically valid git ref/tag can inject shell execution in the affected cp command.
- [x] Confirm the injected command can access signing-step environment secrets and runs before final packaging/release artifact handling.
## Report
Validated the finding. The checked-out commit is 0fb2dfe1e5f6439d0ee8692def56232fd5c705f0. In .github/workflows/release.yml, the workflow is triggered on tags matching v* at lines 3-6. The signing step uses shell: bash and exposes RELEASE_GPG_PRIVATE_KEY, RELEASE_GPG_PASSPHRASE, and RELEASE_GPG_FINGERPRINT at lines 83-89. The newly added vulnerable sinks are direct GitHub expression interpolations into bash source at lines 104 and 106: cp ... "dist/ClipForVRChat-${{ github.ref_name }}-...". Packaging occurs afterwards at lines 108-114, so commands injected there can affect release artifacts. Dynamic reproduction: I simulated GitHub Actions pre-shell interpolation using a valid tag/ref payload `v1`env>leak`x`. `git check-ref-format --allow-onelevel 'v1`env>leak`x'` returned status 0, and the ref starts with v and contains no slash or space. After interpolation, bash receives: `cp "dist/ClipForVRChat/ClipForVRChat.exe.asc" "dist/ClipForVRChat-v1`env>leak`x-windows-amd64.exe.asc"`. Bash executes the command substitution inside the quoted destination. The PoC output showed `++ env` in bash trace and produced a leak file containing `RELEASE_GPG_PRIVATE_KEY=PRIVATE_KEY_SECRET_SENTINEL`, `RELEASE_GPG_PASSPHRASE=PASSPHRASE_SECRET_SENTINEL`, and `RELEASE_GPG_FINGERPRINT=FINGERPRINT_SECRET_SENTINEL`. The quote/semicolon variant from the report, `v1";env>leak;#`, is also accepted by git check-ref-format. Crash/Valgrind/debugger validation is not applicable because this is CI shell command injection rather than a native memory-corruption issue; valgrind and gdb were also not installed in the container.

# Evidence
github/workflows/release.yml (L108 to 114)
  Note: Packaging happens after the injectable signing step, so injected commands can affect the files that are ultimately zipped and released.

github/workflows/release.yml (L3 to 7)
  Note: The workflow can be triggered from tag refs, and tag names are used later as github.ref_name.

github/workflows/release.yml (L83 to 106)
  Note: The signing step exposes release GPG secrets to the Bash process and directly interpolates github.ref_name into shell commands at lines 104 and 106, enabling command injection through crafted ref names.

